1. Create a table comparing at least three types of WAN connections (such as leased line, DSL, and MPLS) with columns for speed, cost, and typical use cases.
=>WAN Type         Speed                                                                         Cost                                              Typical Use Cases
Leased Line     Dedicated symmetric: T1/E1 (1.5-2 Mbps), up to 10 Gbps+               High (most expensive due to dedicated nature)        Point-to-point connections between offices/data centers, high-security needs, constant high-volume traffic (e.g., financial institutions)."
DSL             Asymmetric: Typically 1-100 Mbps download                              Low to moderate (uses existing phone lines)           SOHO/small business internet access, general browsing, email; not ideal for high upload or symmetric needs."
MPLS            2 Mbps to 10 Gbps+ (scalable)                                          High (but offers QoS and managed service)            Enterprise multi-site WANs, latency-sensitive apps (VoIP, ERP), traffic engineering with QoS across provider networks."

2. Draw a labeled diagram (on paper or using any drawing tool) showing how a CSU/DSU connects a router to a WAN service provider, and explain the role of each device in 2-3 sentences.
=>  [Router (CPE)] --- Serial Cable --- [CSU/DSU] === Leased Line / WAN Link === [Service Provider (Telco/CO)]

Router: Customer Premises Equipment (CPE) that routes IP traffic between the local LAN and the WAN.
Serial Cable: Short connection  linking the router's serial interface to the CSU/DSU.
CSU/DSU: Converts digital signals from the router into a format suitable for the telco's line (provides clocking, signal regeneration, and line coding).
WAN Service Provider: Handles the long-distance transmission.

3. List three real-world examples of popular apps or services (like IRCTC, WhatsApp, or Zomato) that rely on WAN connections, and briefly describe how WAN enables their functionality.
=>IRCTC (Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation): India's official rail booking platform. WAN enables global users to access centralized reservation servers over the internet for real-time seat availability, booking, and PNR status checks across vast geographic distances.
WhatsApp: Global messaging and calling app. WAN (via internet backbones) allows end-to-end encrypted text, voice, and video communication between users on different continents, routing messages through distributed servers.
Zomato: Food delivery and restaurant discovery service. WAN connects users' mobile apps to centralized backend servers for real-time order tracking, restaurant listings, payments, and logistics coordination across cities and countries.

